    "IntroductionHigh-energy nucleus-nucleus collisions, such as those at the Large Hadron Collider (LHC) and Relativistic Heavy-Ion Collider (RHIC), provide the unique opportunity to create in the laboratory the conditions of the microsecondold Universe, in particular the color-deconfined state called the Quark-Gluon Plasma (QGP).",
    "The microscopic understanding of the remarkable properties of the QGP and its hadronization remains a key challenge in nuclear physics.The quarkonium families, charmonia and bottomonia, play a critical role in this objective and have long been prominent observables used to probe the fundamental color force in the hot QCD medium.",
    "Theoretically, the vacuum heavyquark (HQ) potential provides a well-calibrated starting point for the study of quarkonium interactions in medium, see Refs.",
    "[1][2][3][4][5] for recent reviews.",
    "In particular, the string term in the HQ potential characterizes the long-range nonperturbative part of the force and is associated with the confining property of QCD."
  ],
